{{notability|bio|date=February 2016}} {{Infobox scientist |name = Andreas Brandstädt |image = |image_size = |caption = |birth_date = {{b-da|17 January 1949}} |birth_place = [[Arnstadt]], [[East Germany]] |death_date = |death_place = |residence = [[Germany]] |citizenship = |nationality = [[Germans|German]] |ethnicity = [[Germans|German]] |fields = [[Mathematician]] |workplaces = [[University of Jena]], [[University of Duisburg]], [[University of Rostock]] |alma_mater = [[University of Jena]] |doctoral_advisor = [[Gerd Wechsung]] |academic_advisors = |doctoral_students = |notable_students = |known_for = [[Graph Theory]]: [[hypertree]]s, [[strongly chordal graph]]s |author_abbrev_bot = |author_abbrev_zoo = |influences = |influenced = |awards = |religion = |signature = <!--(filename only)--> |footnotes = }}
'''Andreas Brandstädt''' (born 17 January 1949 in [[Arnstadt]], [[East Germany]]) is a [[Germany|German]] [[mathematician]] and [[computer scientist]].
==Life and work== He graduated from the Friedrich Schiller [[University of Jena]], [[Germany]], with a Ph.D. (Dr. rer. nat.) in stochastics in 1976 and a habilitation (Dr. sc. nat.) in complexity theory in 1983. Since 1974 he worked there in the group of his academic teacher [[Gerd Wechsung]].
From 1991 to 1994, he was the professor for Computer Science in the Department of Mathematics, <ref>https://www.uni-due.de/mathematik/en_index.php</ref> at the [[University of Duisburg]], Germany, and from 1994 to 2014 he was the professor for Theoretical Computer Science<ref>http://users.informatik.uni-rostock.de/~ab</ref> at the [[University of Rostock]], Germany.
He was a visiting professor at the universities of [[University of Metz|Metz]], [[University of Amiens|Amiens]], and [[University of Clermont-Ferrand|Clermont-Ferrand]] ([[France]]) and at the [[University of Primorska]] in [[Koper]] ([[Slovenia]]). He was Invited Speaker at various conferences in [[Argentina]], [[Austria]], [[Belarus]], [[Brasil]], [[Canada]], [[China]], [[France]], [[Greece]], [[India]], [[Israel]], [[Norway]], [[Poland]], [[Slovenia]], and [[Switzerland]].
Brandstädt is an active researcher in [[graph algorithms]], [[discrete mathematics]], [[combinatorial optimization]], and [[graph theory]]. A frequently used tool in his papers is tree structure of graphs and hypergraphs such as for [[hypertree]]s, [[strongly chordal graph]]s and [[chordal graph]]s.
He frequently took part in program committees such as Workshop on Graph-Theoretic Concepts in Computer Science (and three times was a co-organizer of this conference) and is member of the [[Editorial Board]] of [[Discrete Applied Mathematics]].<ref>http://www.journals.elsevier.com/discrete-applied-mathematics/editorial-board/ Editorial Board of Discrete Applied Mathematics</ref>
