'''John W. Dawson Jr.''' (born February 4, 1944)<ref>{{cite LAF|id=n 96115290}}</ref> is Professor of Mathematics, Emeritus at [[Penn State York|Pennsylvania State University at York]]. Born in [[Wichita, Kansas]], he attended [[M.I.T.]] as a [[National Merit Scholar]] before earning a doctorate in [[mathematical logic]] from the [[University of Michigan]] in 1972.<ref>[http://genealogy.math.ndsu.nodak.edu/id.php?id=5344 John William Dawson Jr.], [[Mathematics Genealogy Project]]. Accessed January 28, 2010</ref> An internationally recognized authority on the life and work of [[Kurt Gödel]], Professor Dawson is the author of numerous articles on [[axiomatic set theory]] and the history of [[modern logic]]. During the years 1982 to 1984, he catalogued Gödel's papers at the [[Institute for Advanced Study]] in [[Princeton, New Jersey|Princeton]], and afterward he served as a co-editor of Gödel's Collected Works. He recently retired as co-Editor-in-Chief of the journal ''History and Philosophy of Logic''.<ref>[http://www.tandf.co.uk/journals/journal.asp?issn=0144-5340&linktype=5 Editorial Board,] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100704145934/http://www.tandf.co.uk/journals/journal.asp?issn=0144-5340&linktype=5 |date=2010-07-04 }} ''History and Philosophy of Logic'', [[Taylor and Francis]]. Accessed January 28, 2010</ref>
