{{Infobox scientist | name = Roy L. Adler | image = Roy adler.jpg <!--(filename only, i.e. without "File:" prefix)--> | image_size = | alt = | caption = Roy Adler, Oberwolfach 1968 | birth_date = {{birth date|1931|2|22|mf=y}} | birth_place = [[Newark, New Jersey]]<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.ams.org/notices/199708/bios.pdf|title=Biographies of Candidates 1997|work=[[Notices of the American Mathematical Society]]|volume=44|number=8|date=September 1997|page=967|accessdate=2 December 2016}}</ref> | death_date = {{death date and age |2016|07|26|1931|02|22}} | death_place = [[Chappaqua, New York]] | nationality = [[United States|American]] | fields = [[Mathematics]] | workplaces = [[Thomas J. Watson Research Center]] | alma_mater = [[Yale University]] | doctoral_advisor = [[Shizuo Kakutani]] <!--(or | doctoral_advisors = )--> | doctoral_students = | known_for = | awards = }}
'''Roy Lee Adler''' (February 22, 1931 – July 26, 2016<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/nytimes/obituary.aspx?pid=180817333|title=Roy Adler Obituary - Mount Kisco, NY|work=The New York Times|date=July 29, 2016|accessdate=2 December 2016}}</ref>) was an American mathematician.
Adler earned his Ph.D. in 1961 from [[Yale University]] under the supervision of [[Shizuo Kakutani]] (''On some algebraic aspects of measure preserving transformations'').<ref>[http://www.genealogy.math.ndsu.nodak.edu/id.php?id=9153 Mathematics Genealogy Project]</ref> He then worked as a mathematician for IBM at the [[Thomas J. Watson Research Center]].
Adler studies [[dynamical system]]s, [[ergodic theory]], [[symbolic dynamics|symbolic]] and [[topological dynamic]]s and [[coding theory]]. The [[road coloring problem]] that was solved by [[Avraham Trakhtman]] in 2007 came from him, along with [[L. W. Goodwyn]] and [[Benjamin Weiss]].
He was a fellow of the [[American Mathematical Society]].<ref>[http://www.ams.org/profession/fellows-list List of Fellows of the American Mathematical Society], retrieved 2013-11-24.</ref>
== Writings == *With Brian Marcus: Topological entropy and equivalence of dynamical systems, American Mathematical Society 1979 *With Benjamin Weiss: Similarity of automorphisms of the torus, Memoirs AMS 1970 *[http://www.ams.org/journals/bull/1998-35-01/S0273-0979-98-00737-X/ Symbolic dynamics and Markov partitions, Bulletin AMS, volume 35, 1998, pg. 1-57] *With L. W. Goodwyn, B. Weiss: ''Equivalence of topological Markov shifts'', Israel J. Math., volume 27, 1977, pg. 49-63 *With [[Alan Konheim]], M. H. McAndrew ''Topological Entropy'', Transactions AMS, volume 114, 1965, pg. 309-319 *[http://www.scholarpedia.org/article/Topological_entropy Topological Entropy, in Scholarpedia] *With Charles Tresser, Patrick A. Worfolk ''Topological conjugacy of linear endomorphisms of the 2-torus'', Trans. Amer. Math. Soc. 349 (1997), 1633–1652 *With B. Weiss ''Entropy, a complete metric invariant for automorphisms of the torus'', Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A. 57 (1967), 1573–1576
